{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0147TtVjhp2a8iASmAE8vALK","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture:\n1. The `es-file-realm-aggregate` secret has `users`, `users_roles`, and `roles.yml` keys\n2. The `elastic` user is not in the file realm - it's the built-in user with the password set via keystore (or the `ELASTIC_PASSWORD` env var)\n3. The app-data index has `_tier_preference: data_content` routing\n\nNow let me understand the init container behavior. The `es-file-realm-aggregate` secret has ops-user and report-user, NOT the elastic user. \n\nI'm realizing the init container `set-elastic-password` is trying to write the elastic user to the file realm config, but it can't modify the secret volume directly. Let me look more carefully at how the volumes are mounted in the StatefulSet - the secret is being mounted with specific keys mapped to file paths, and I need to see what the init container actually has access to. Actually, I need to reconsider this. Kubernetes secret volumes are backed by tmpfs, which is writable, so the init container should be able to write to files in that mount. Let me think through how Kubernetes actually projects the secret data—it creates a tmpfs filesystem and writes the secret files into it, which means new files can be created and existing ones potentially modified.\n\nSo the init container that overwrites the user files should work fine. For the new data nodes, I'd apply the same init container pattern using the existing secret that aggregates the file realm data.\n\nWait, I'm noticing something about the init container command - it's writing the elastic password in plaintext to the users file, but Elasticsearch file realm actually requires bcrypt-hashed passwords. The command echoes `elastic:$(cat /run/secrets/elastic-pass)` which would be plaintext, not hashed. Though looking at the ES documentation, file realm does support both plaint