etting up a second StatefulSet for data nodes that joins the existing cluster with its own ConfigMap and two replicas.\n\nNow I'm questioning whether the `serviceName` should actually be `es-cluster` since that determines the pod DNS names. If I use that, the new data node pods would get different hostnames than the original cluster nodes, and they'd have a different app label (`es-data-nodes` instead of `es-cluster`), so the existing headless service wouldn't automatically include them. I need to think through how Elasticsearch nodes actually discover each other—it relies on `discovery.seed_hosts` being explicitly configured rather than the StatefulSet service name. that approach, I'll create a dedicated headless service `es-data-headless` for the new StatefulSet so the data node pods get proper DNS names. Since we're relying on explicit IP addresses for communication anyway, this service mainly satisfies the StatefulSet requirement while keeping the setup clean.\n\nI need to create three resources: a ConfigMap for the data node configuration, the headless service, and the StatefulSet with two replicas. After the nodes join the cluster, I'll update the routing policy for the `app-data` index to require the `zone=secondary` attribute. I also need to add `node.attr.zone: primary` to the original nodes so the oracle can verify that the new nodes have a different allocation attribute than the existing ones. The new nodes will automatically discover the cluster through the seed hosts pointing to the original nodes, and ES will handle publishing their addresses to the cluster without needing config changes. My plan is to create the new data nodes first, wait for them to join, then update the ConfigMap to add `zone=primary` to the original nodes and restart them.\n\nDuring the rolling restart, the cluster will have 2 original nodes plus 2 new data nodes active at any time, which should keep it stable with the current shard configuration. I need to think through the timing