w data node pods, but the StatefulSet just needs the service to exist for DNS naming purposes. Let me reconsider how StatefulSet DNS actually works. The StatefulSet controller creates DNS records for each pod in the format `{pod-name}.{service-name}.{namespace}.svc.cluster.local`, but this requires the headless service to exist and the pod's labels to match the service selector. I'm checking the Kubernetes documentation to clarify whether DNS records are created purely by the StatefulSet or if they depend on the service selector matching.\n\nActually, I think the key insight is that StatefulSets automatically set the pod's `subdomain` field to the service name, which causes DNS records to be created regardless of selector matching. But creating a dedicated headless service for the data nodes feels like the cleaner approach, so I'll go with that instead.\n\nMy implementation plan is to create a ConfigMap for the secondary zone, a headless service for the data nodes, a StatefulSet with two replicas, update the existing config to mark the primary zone, wait for the nodes to join, configure app-data routing, and then do a rolling restart of the original nodes to pick up the zone label.\n\nNow I'm writing out the YAML configuration...\n\nActually, let me reconsider the headless service setup one more time. I need to verify how the original es-cluster service is configured and ensure the StatefulSet pods will properly get DNS names through the headless service, which requires the pods to have a subdomain matching the service name.\n\nFor this approach, I'll create a dedicated headless service called `es-data` that the StatefulSet will reference. This keeps things cleaner and avoids any conflicts with the existing setup.\n\nWriting the YAML...","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":855,"cache_read_input_tokens":45736,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_i