{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01KjJpnCRg7ZpGnURJVLhoNx","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So the original pods also use the secret for es-users. But then how did the init container succeed? Let me check what `es-file-realm-aggregate` contains versus what's actually on the pods.\n\nWait, let me reread the init container output. It said the writes fail because of read-only file system. But the original pods ARE running... \n\nActually wait - for the original pods, the init container output: I got `Exit code 1` for `kubectl logs es-cluster-0 -c set-elastic-password`. This is because the container has already completed (exited), so the logs command might fail. Let me try with `--previous` or just check the current pod status.\n \nHmm, but the original pod has zero restarts, which means the init container must have succeeded on the first try. That's strange if the file system is read-only. Let me look at the actual pod description to see what the init container status shows.\n\nActually, I'm noticing the restart annotation on the pods—they were restarted at some point, so maybe the volume configuration changed. Let me check if the running pod is actually using an `emptyDir` instead of the secret, or if Kubernetes secret volumes aren't actually read-only at the kernel level like I assumed.\n\nAh, I see it now—secret volumes in Kubernetes are backed by tmpfs, which is writable. The files are projected with mode 0644 owned by root, so if the init container runs as root, it should be able to overwrite them. The Elasticsearch image typically runs as the `elasticsearch` user, but the init container might have different permissions. The error message says \"Read-only file system\" rather than \"Permission denied,\" which suggests the filesystem itself is mounted read-only, not just the files.\n\nLooking at the original pods, they're running successfully, so either the actual running pod has a different volume configuration than what the StatefulSet YAML shows, or there's something about how init container failures are being handled. Since init container failures should cause a CrashLoopBackOff, I need to check the actual init container status more carefully.\n\nThe `kubectl logs` command returning exit code 1 might just mean the container has already completed (since it's an init container), not that it actually failed. Let me examine the pod's init container statuses directly to see what's really happening.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":178,"cache_read_input_tokens":57285,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":178},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"d6cd69cb-8e3d-47f2-bc2e-a8081d5ee49f","uuid":"3ba93fff-f5db-43ab-b811-2c7c1e985d01","request_id":"req_011Cc9ba6pcPqFxV7qkH9G4z"}
